# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: graphql
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:graphql/graphql] Facebook started GraphQL development in 2012 and released a draft specification and reference implementation as open source in 2015.
[src:graphql/graphql] In 2018, GraphQL was moved to the newly established GraphQL Foundation, hosted by the non-profit Linux Foundation.
[src:graphql/graphql] On February 9, 2018, the GraphQL Schema Definition Language became part of the specification.
[src:graphql/graphql] Many popular public APIs adopted GraphQL as the default way to access them.
[src:graphql/graphql] These include public APIs of Facebook, GitHub, Yelp, Shopify, Google Directions API and many others.
[src:graphql/graphql] There is an annual GraphQL Conference featuring new developments of the protocol and organizations successfully using GraphQL.
[src:graphql/graphql] The event is hosted by the GraphQL Foundation with previous organizers incl.
[src:graphql/graphql] GraphQL supports reading, writing (mutating), and subscribing to changes to data (realtime updates – commonly implemented using WebSockets).
[src:graphql/graphql] A GraphQL service is created by defining types with fields, then providing functions to resolve the data for each field.
[src:graphql/graphql] The types and fields make up what is known as the *schema definition*.
[src:graphql/graphql] The functions that retrieve and map the data are called *resolvers*.
[src:graphql/graphql] After being validated against the schema, a GraphQL query is executed by the server.
[src:graphql/graphql] The server returns a result that mirrors the shape of the original query, typically as JSON.
[src:graphql/graphql] With GraphQL, a business domain is modeled as a graph by defining a schema; within this schema, different types of nodes and their relations are defined.
[src:graphql/graphql] The GraphQL type system describes what data can be queried from the API.
[src:graphql/graphql] The collection of those capabilities is referred to as the service's *schema* and clients can use that schema to send queries to the API that return predictable results.
[src:graphql/graphql] The root type of a GraphQL schema, `Query` by default, contains all of the fields that can be queried.
[src:graphql/graphql] Other types define the objects and fields that the GraphQL server can return.
[src:graphql/graphql] There are several base types, called scalars, to represent things like strings, numbers, and IDs.
[src:graphql/graphql] Fields are defined as nullable by default, and a trailing exclamation mark can be used to make a field non-nullable (required).
[src:graphql/graphql] A field can be defined as a list by wrapping the field's type in square brackets (for example, `authors: [String]`).
[src:graphql/graphql] A GraphQL query defines the exact shape of the data needed by the client.
[src:graphql/graphql] Once validated and executed by the GraphQL server, the data is returned in the same shape.
[src:graphql/graphql] A GraphQL mutation allows for data to be created, updated, or deleted.
[src:graphql/graphql] Mutations generally contain *variables*, which allow data to be passed into the server from the client.
[src:graphql/graphql] The mutation also defines the shape of the data that will be returned to the client after the operation is complete.
[src:graphql/graphql] The variables are passed as an object with fields that match the variable names in the mutation.
[src:graphql/graphql] Once the operation is complete, the GraphQL server will return data matching the shape defined by the mutation.
[src:graphql/graphql] GraphQL also supports live updates sent from the server to client in an operation called a subscription.
[src:graphql/graphql] Again, the client defines the shape of the data that it needs whenever an update is made.
[src:graphql/graphql] When a mutation is made through the GraphQL server that updates the associated field, data is sent to all subscribed clients in the format setup through the subscription.
[src:graphql/graphql] While there's nothing that prevents a GraphQL service from being versioned just like any other API, GraphQL takes a strong opinion on avoiding versioning by providing the tools for the continuous evolution of a GraphQL schema.
[src:graphql/graphql] The `@deprecated` *built-in directive* is used within the type system definition language to indicate deprecated portions of a GraphQL service's schema, such as deprecated fields on a type or deprecated enum values.
[src:graphql/graphql] GraphQL only returns the data that's explicitly requested, so new capabilities can be added via new types or new fields on existing types without creating a breaking change.
[src:graphql/graphql] This has led to a common practice of always avoiding breaking changes and serving a versionless API.
[src:graphql/graphql] GraphQL does not provide a full-fledged graph query language such as SPARQL, or even in dialects of SQL that support transitive closure.
[src:graphql/graphql] For example, a GraphQL interface that reports the parents of an individual cannot return, in a single query, the set of all their ancestors.
[src:graphql/graphql] GraphQL APIs can be tested manually or with automated tools issuing GraphQL requests and verifying the correctness of the results.
[src:graphql/graphql] Automatic test generation is also possible.
[src:graphql/graphql] New requests may be produced through search-based techniques due to a typed schema and introspection capabilities.
[src:graphql/graphql] Some of the software tools used for testing GraphQL implementations include Postman, Beeceptor, GraphiQL, Apollo Studio, GraphQL Hive, GraphQL Editor, and Step CI.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] After a parsed document is validated, a client’s request will be executed by the GraphQL server and the returned result will mirror the shape of the requested query.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] On this page, you’ll learn about the execution phase of GraphQL operations where data is read from or written to an existing source depending on what fields are requested by a client.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] GraphQL cannot execute operations without a type system, so let’s use an example type system to illustrate executing a query.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] You can think of each field in a GraphQL query as a function or method of the previous type which returns the next type.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] This is exactly how GraphQL works—each field on each type is backed by a *resolver function* that is written by the GraphQL server developer.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] When a field is executed, the corresponding resolver is called to produce the next value.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] If a field produces a scalar value like a string or number, then the execution completes.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] However, if a field produces an object value then the query will contain another selection of fields that apply to that object.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] This continues until the leaf values are reached.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] GraphQL queries always end at Scalar or Enum types.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] At the top level of every GraphQL server is an Object type that represents the possible entry points into the GraphQL API, it’s often called “the `query` root operation type” or the `Query` type.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] If the API supports mutations to write data and subscriptions to fetch real-time data as well, then it will have `Mutation` and `Subscription` types that expose fields to perform these kinds of operations too.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] You can learn more about these types on the Schema and Types page.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] In this example, our `Query` type provides a field called `human` which accepts the argument `id`.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] This example is written in JavaScript, however GraphQL servers can be built in many different languages.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Note that while a query operation could technically write data to the underlying data system during its execution, mutation operations are conventionally used for requests that produce side effects during their execution.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] And because mutation operations produce side effects, GraphQL implementations can be expected to execute these fields serially.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] The `id` argument in the GraphQL query specifies the user whose data is requested, while `context` provides access to retrieve this data from a database.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Since loading from a database is an asynchronous operation, this returns a Promise.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] In JavaScript, Promises are used to work with asynchronous values, but the same concept exists in many languages, often called *Futures*, *Tasks*, or *Deferred*.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] When the database returns the data, we can construct and return a new `Human` object.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Notice that while the resolver function needs to be aware of Promises, the GraphQL query does not.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] It simply expects the `human` field to return something that can be further resolved to a scalar `name` value.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] During execution, GraphQL will wait for Promises, Futures, and Tasks to be completed before continuing and will do so with optimal concurrency.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] A GraphQL server is powered by a type system that is used to determine what to do next.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Even before the `human` field returns anything, GraphQL knows the next step will be to resolve fields on the `Human` type since the type system tells it that the `human` field will return this output type.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Resolving the name in this case is straightforward.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] The name resolver function is called and the `obj` argument is the new `Human` object returned from the previous field.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] In this case, we expect this object to have a `name` property, which we can read and return directly.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Many GraphQL libraries let you omit resolvers this simple, assuming that if a resolver isn’t provided for a field, a property of the same name should be read and returned.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] While the `name` field is being resolved, the `appearsIn` and `starships` fields can be resolved concurrently.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Notice that our type system claims `appearsIn` will return Enum types with known values, however, this function is returning numbers!
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Indeed if we look up at the result we’ll see that the appropriate values for the Enum type are being returned.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] This is an example of *scalar coercion*.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] The type system knows what to expect and will convert the values returned by a resolver function into something that upholds the API contract.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] In this case, there may be an Enum type defined on our server that uses numbers like `4`, `5`, and `6` internally, but represents them as the expected values in the GraphQL type system.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] We’ve already seen some of what happens when a field returns a list of things with the `appearsIn` field above.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] It returned a List type containing Enum type values, and since that’s what the type system expected, each item in the list was coerced to the appropriate value.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] What happens when the `starships` field is resolved?
[src:graphql/learn-execution] The resolver for this field is not just returning a Promise, it’s returning a *list* of Promises.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] The `Human` object had a list of IDs of the `Starships` they piloted, but we need to load all of those IDs to get real Starship objects.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] GraphQL will wait for all of these Promises concurrently before continuing, and when left with a list of objects, it will continue yet again to load the `name` field on each of these items concurrently.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] As each field is resolved, the resulting value is placed into a key-value map with the field name (or alias) as the key and the resolved value as the value.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] This continues from the bottom leaf fields of the query back up to the original field on the root `Query` type.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Collectively these produce a structure that mirrors the original query which can then be sent (typically as JSON) to the client that requested it.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] As we can see, each field in the nested selection sets resolves to a scalar leaf value during execution of the query.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Now that we understand how operations are executed, we can move to the last stage of the lifecycle of a GraphQL request where the response is delivered to a client.
[src:graphql/learn-execution] Explore how GraphQL structures its responses, including data, errors and extensions for custom metadata.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Most discussions of GraphQL focus on data fetching, but any complete data platform needs a way to modify server-side data as well.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] In REST, any request might cause some side-effects on the server, but by convention, it’s suggested that one doesn’t use `GET` requests to modify data.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] On this page, you’ll learn how to use mutation operations to write data using GraphQL, and do so in a way that supports client use cases.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] All of the features of GraphQL operations that apply to queries also apply to mutations, so review the Queries page first before proceeding.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] When creating new data with a REST API, you would send a `POST` request to a specific endpoint and include information about the entities to be created in the body of the request.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Like queries, mutation fields are added to one of the root operation types that provide an entry point to the API.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] In this case, we define the `createReview` field on the `Mutation` type.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Mutation fields can also accept arguments and you might notice that the `review` argument has an input type set to `ReviewInput`.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] This is known as Input Object type, which allows us to pass in a structured object containing information the mutation can use instead of individual scalar values only.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] While the `createReview` field could be defined with any valid output type in the schema, it’s conventional to specify an output type that relates to whatever is modified during the mutation—in this case, the `Review` type.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] This can be useful for clients that need to fetch the new state of an object after an update.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Recall that GraphQL is meant to work with your existing code and data, so the actual creation of the review is up to you when clients send this operation to the GraphQL server.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] You can learn more about how GraphQL provides data for fields on the Execution page.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Similarly, we use mutations to update existing data.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] The previous example demonstrates an important distinction from REST.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] To update a human’s properties using a REST API, you would likely send any updated data to a generalized endpoint for that resource using a `PATCH` request.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] With GraphQL, instead of simply creating an `updateHuman` mutation, you can define more specific mutation fields such as `updateHumanName`that are designed for the task at hand.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Purpose-built mutation fields can help make a schema more expressive by allowing the input types for field arguments to be Non-Null types (a generic `updateHuman` mutation would likely need to accept many nullable arguments to handle different update scenarios).
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Defining this requirement in the schema also eliminates the need for other runtime logic to determine that the appropriate values were submitted to perform the client’s desired write operation.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] GraphQL also allows us to express relationships between data that would be more difficult to model semantically with a basic CRUD-style request.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] For example, a user may wish to save a personal rating for a film.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] As a general rule, a GraphQL API should be designed to help clients get and modify data in a way that makes sense for them, so the fields defined in a schema should be informed by those use cases.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] As with mutations that create and update data, the GraphQL specification doesn’t indicate what should be returned from a successful mutation operation that deletes data, but we do have to specify some type as an output type for the field in the schema.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Commonly, the deleted entity’s ID or a payload object containing data about the entity will be used to indicate that the operation was successful.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] A mutation can contain multiple fields, just like a query.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Serial execution of these top-level fields means that if we send two `deleteStarship` mutations in one request, the first is guaranteed to finish before the second begins, ensuring that we don’t end up in a race condition with ourselves.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Note that serial execution of top-level `Mutation` fields differs from the notion of a database transaction.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Some mutation fields may resolve successfully while others return errors, and there’s no way for GraphQL to revert the successful portions of the operation when this happens.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] So in the previous example, if the first starship is removed successfully but the `secondShip` field raises an error, there is no built-in way for GraphQL to revert the execution of the `firstShip` field afterward.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Now that we know how to use a GraphQL server to read and write data, we’re ready to learn how to fetch data in real time using subscriptions.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] You may also wish to learn more about how GraphQL queries and mutations can be served over HTTP.
[src:graphql/learn-mutations] Discover how GraphQL supports real-time data with subscriptions and how to use them effectively at scale.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] GraphQL supports three main operation types—queries, mutations, and subscriptions.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] We have already seen several examples of basic queries in this guide, and on this page, you’ll learn in detail how to use the various features of query operations to read data from a server.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] At its simplest, GraphQL is about asking for specific fields on objects.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] When creating a GraphQL *document* we always start with a root operation type (the `Query` Object type for this example) because it serves as an entry point to the API.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] From there we must specify the *selection set* of fields we are interested in, all the way down to their leaf values which will be Scalar or Enum types.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] The field `name` returns a `String` type, in this case the name of the main hero of Star Wars, `"R2-D2"`.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] The GraphQL specification indicates that a request’s result will be returned on a top-level `data` key in the response.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] If the request raised any errors, there will be information about what went wrong on a top-level `errors` key.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] From there, you can see that the result has the same shape as the query.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] This is essential to GraphQL, because you always get back what you expect, and the server knows exactly what fields the client is asking for.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In the previous example, we just asked for the name of our hero which returned a `String`, but fields can also return Object types (and lists thereof).
[src:graphql/learn-queries] GraphQL queries can traverse related objects and their fields, letting clients fetch lots of related data in one request, instead of making several roundtrips as one would need in a classic REST architecture.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Note that in this example, the `friends` field returns an array of items.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] GraphQL queries look the same for single items or lists of items; however, we know which one to expect based on what is indicated in the schema.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] If the only thing we could do was traverse objects and their fields, GraphQL would already be a very useful language for data fetching.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In a system like REST, you can only pass a single set of arguments—the query parameters and URL segments in your request.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] But in GraphQL, every field and nested object can get its own set of arguments, making GraphQL a complete replacement for making multiple API fetches.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Arguments can be of many different types.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In the above example, we have used an Enum type, which represents one of a finite set of options (in this case, units of length, either `METER` or `FOOT`).
[src:graphql/learn-queries] GraphQL comes with a default set of types, but a GraphQL server can also declare custom types, as long as they can be serialized into your transport format.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Read more about the GraphQL type system here.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In the examples above we have been using a shorthand syntax where we omit the `query` keyword before the operation’s selection set.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In addition to specifying the *operation type* explicitly, we can also add a unique *operation name*, which is useful in production apps because it makes debugging and tracing easier.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] The operation type is either `query`, `mutation`, or `subscription` and describes what type of operation you intend to do.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] This keyword is required unless you’re using the shorthand syntax for queries (it is always required for mutations and subscriptions).
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Additionally, if you wish to provide a name for your operation, then you must specify the operation type as well.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] The operation name is an explicit name that you assign to your operation; you should pick a meaningful name.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] It is required when sending multiple operations in one document, but even if you’re only sending one operation it’s encouraged because operation names are helpful for debugging and server-side logging.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] When something goes wrong (you see errors either in your network logs or in the logs of your GraphQL server) it is easier to identify a query in your codebase by name instead of trying to decipher the contents.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Think of this just like a function name in your favorite programming language.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] For example, in JavaScript, we can easily work only with anonymous functions, but when we give a function a name, it’s easier to track it down, debug our code, and log when it’s called.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In the same way, GraphQL query and mutation names, along with fragment names, can be a useful debugging tool on the server side to identify different GraphQL requests.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] If you have a sharp eye, you may have noticed that, since the result object fields match the name of the fields in the query but don’t include arguments, you can’t directly query for the same field with different arguments.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] That’s why you need aliases—they let you rename the result of a field to anything you want.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In the above example, the two `hero` fields would have conflicted, but since we can alias them to different names, we can get both results in one request.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] So far, we have been writing all of our arguments inside the query string.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] But in most applications, the arguments to fields will be dynamic.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] For example, there might be a dropdown that lets you select which Star Wars episode you are interested in, or a search field, or a set of filters.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] It wouldn’t be a good idea to pass these dynamic arguments directly in the query string, because then our client-side code would need to dynamically manipulate the query string at runtime, and serialize it into a GraphQL-specific format.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Instead, GraphQL has a first-class way to factor dynamic values out of the query and pass them as a separate dictionary.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] You must specify an operation type and name in a GraphQL document to use variables.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Now, in our client code, we can simply pass a different variable rather than needing to construct an entirely new query.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In general, this is also a good practice for denoting which arguments in our query are expected to be dynamic—we should never be doing string interpolation to construct queries from user-supplied values.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] The variable definitions are the part that looks like `($episode: Episode)` in the query above.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] It works just like the argument definitions for a function in a typed language.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] It lists all of the variables, prefixed by `$`, followed by their type, in this case, `Episode`.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] All declared variables must be either Scalar, Enum, or Input Object types.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] So if you want to pass a complex object into a field, you need to know what input type matches it on the server.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Variable definitions can be optional or required.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In the case above, since there isn’t an `!` next to the `Episode` type, it’s optional.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] But if the field you are passing the variable into requires a non-null argument, then the variable has to be required as well.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] To learn more about the syntax for these variable definitions, it’s useful to learn schema definition language (SDL), which is explained in detail on the Schemas and Types page.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] When default values are provided for all variables, you can call the query without passing any variables.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] If any variables are passed as part of the variables dictionary, they will override the defaults.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Let’s say we have a relatively complicated page in our app, which lets us look at two heroes side by side, along with their friends.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] You can imagine that such a query could quickly get complicated because we would need to repeat the fields at least once—one for each side of the comparison.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] That’s why GraphQL includes reusable units called fragments.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Fragments let you construct sets of fields, and then include them in queries where needed.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] You can see how the above query would be pretty repetitive if we weren’t able to use fragments.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] The concept of fragments is frequently used to split complicated application data requirements into smaller chunks, especially when you need to combine many UI components with different fragments into one initial data fetch.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Like many other type systems, GraphQL schemas include the ability to define Interface and Union types.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] You can learn more about them on the Schemas and Types page.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] If you are querying a field that returns an Interface or a Union type, you will need to use *inline fragments* to access data on the underlying concrete type.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In this query, the `hero` field returns the type `Character`, which might be either a `Human` or a `Droid` depending on the `episode` argument.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In the direct selection, you can only ask for fields on the `Character` interface, such as `name`.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] To ask for a field on the concrete type, you need to use an inline fragment with a type condition.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Because the first fragment is labeled as `... on Droid`, the `primaryFunction` field will only be executed if the `Character` returned from `hero` is of the `Droid` type.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Similarly for the `height` field for the `Human` type.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Named fragments can also be used in the same way, since a named fragment always has a type attached.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] As we have seen with Union types, there are some situations where you don’t know what type you’ll get back from the GraphQL service so you need some way to determine how to handle that data on the client.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In the above query, `search` returns a Union type that can be one of three options.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Without the `__typename` field, it would be impossible for a client to tell the different types apart.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] All field names beginning with two underscores (`__`) are reserved by GraphQL.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] In addition to `__typename`, GraphQL services provide the `__schema` and `__type` meta-fields which expose the introspection system.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] We discussed above how variables enable us to avoid doing manual string interpolation to construct dynamic queries.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Passing variables in arguments solves a large class of these problems, but we might also need a way to dynamically change the structure and shape of our queries using variables.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] For example, we can imagine a UI component that has a summarized and detailed view, where one includes more fields than the other.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Try editing the variables above to instead pass `true` for `withFriends`, and see how the result changes.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] We needed to use a feature in GraphQL called a directive.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Specifically, an *executable directive* can be attached to a field or fragment inclusion by a client, and can affect execution of the query in any way the server desires.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Directives can be useful to get out of situations where you otherwise would need to do string manipulation to add and remove fields in your query.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Server implementations may also add experimental features by defining completely new directives.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Looking for information on how to define directives that can be used to annotate the types, fields, or arguments in your GraphQL schema?
[src:graphql/learn-queries] See the Schemas and Types page for more information on defining and using type system directives.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Now that we understand the ins and outs of how to read data from a GraphQL server with query operations, it’s time to learn how to change data and trigger side effects using mutations.
[src:graphql/learn-queries] Explore how to modify data with mutations, including how to update and remove records through your schema.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] The collection of those capabilities is referred to as the service’s *schema* and clients can use that schema to send queries to the API that return predictable results.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] On this page, we’ll explore GraphQL’s six kinds of named type definitions as well as other features of the type system to learn how they may be used to describe your data and the relationships between them.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Since GraphQL can be used with any backend framework or programming language, we’ll avoid implementation-specific details and talk only about the concepts.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] If you’ve seen a GraphQL query before, you know that the GraphQL query language is basically about selecting fields on objects.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Because the shape of a GraphQL query closely matches the result, we can predict what the query will return without knowing that much about the server.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] But it’s useful to have an exact description of the data we can request.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] What kinds of objects might they return?
[src:graphql/learn-schema] What fields are available on those sub-objects?
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Every GraphQL service defines a set of types that completely describe the set of possible data we can query on that service.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Then, when requests come in, they are validated and executed against that schema.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Since we can’t rely on a specific programming language to discuss GraphQL schemas in this guide, we’ll use SDL because it’s similar to the query language that we’ve seen so far and allows us to talk about GraphQL schemas in a language-agnostic way.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] The most basic components of a GraphQL schema are Object types, which just represent a kind of object you can fetch from your service, and what fields it has.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Now you know what a GraphQL Object type looks like and how to read the basics of SDL.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Unlike languages such as JavaScript and Python where functions take a list of ordered arguments, all arguments in GraphQL are passed by name specifically.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In this case, the `length` field has one defined argument called `unit`.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Arguments can be either required or optional.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] When an argument is optional, we can define a *default value*.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] If the `unit` argument is not passed, then it will be set to `METER` by default.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Every GraphQL schema must support `query` operations.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] The *entry point* for this root operation type is a regular Object type called `Query` by default.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Schemas may also support `mutation` and `subscription` operations by adding additional `Mutation` and `Subscription` types and then defining fields on the corresponding root operation types.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] It’s important to remember that other than the special status of being entry points into the schema, the `Query`, `Mutation`, and `Subscription` types are the same as any other GraphQL Object type, and their fields work exactly the same way.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] A GraphQL Object type has a name and fields, but at some point, those fields must resolve to some concrete data.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] That’s where the Scalar types come in: they represent the leaf values of the query.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] We know this because those fields don’t have any sub-fields—they are the leaves of the query.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In most GraphQL service implementations, there is also a way to specify custom Scalar types.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Then it’s up to our implementation to define how that type should be serialized, deserialized, and validated.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] For example, you could specify that the `Date` type should always be serialized into an integer timestamp, and your client should know to expect that format for any date fields.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Enum types, also known as enumeration types, are a special kind of scalar that is restricted to a particular set of allowed values.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] This means that wherever we use the type `Episode` in our schema, we expect it to be exactly one of `NEWHOPE`, `EMPIRE`, or `JEDI`.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] GraphQL service implementations in various languages will have a language-specific way of dealing with Enum types.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In languages that support enums as a first-class citizen, the implementation might take advantage of that; in a language like JavaScript with no enum support, these values might be internally mapped to a set of integers.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] However, these details don’t leak out to the client, which can operate entirely in terms of the string names of the Enum type’s values.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Types are assumed to be nullable and singular by default in GraphQL.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] However, when you use these named types in a schema (or in query variable declarations) you can apply additional *type modifiers* that will affect the meaning of those values.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] As we saw with the Object type example above, GraphQL supports two type modifiers—the List and Non-Null types—and they can be used individually or in combination with each other.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Here, we’re using a `String` type and marking it as a Non-Null type by adding an exclamation mark (`!`) after the type name.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] This means that our server always expects to return a non-null value for this field, and if the resolver produces a null value, then that will trigger a GraphQL execution error, letting the client know that something has gone wrong.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] We can use a type modifier to mark a type as a List type, which indicates that this field will return an array of that type.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In SDL, this is denoted by wrapping the type in square brackets, `[` and `]`.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] It works the same for arguments, where the validation step will expect an array for that value.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] As we see above, the Non-Null and List modifiers can be combined.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] This means that the *list itself* can be null, but it can’t have any null members.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] You can arbitrarily nest any number of Non-Null and List modifiers, according to your needs.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In GraphQL, there is no way to define a type so that the field’s data will only be considered valid if a non-empty list is provided.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] would still be a valid response for a Non-Null List of a Non-Null type.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Like many type systems, GraphQL supports *abstract types*.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] The first of these types that we’ll explore is an Interface type, which defines a certain set of fields that a concrete Object type or other Interface type must also include to implement it.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] This means that any type that *implements* `Character` needs to have these exact fields as well as the same arguments and return types.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] You can see that both of these types have all of the fields from the `Character` Interface type, but also bring in extra fields—`totalCredits`, `starships` and `primaryFunction`—that are specific to that particular type of character.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Interface types are useful when you want to return an object or set of objects, but those might be of several different types.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] The `hero` field returns the type `Character`, which means it might be either a `Human` or a `Droid` depending on the `episode` argument.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In the query above, you can only ask for fields that exist on the `Character` Interface type, which doesn’t include `primaryFunction`.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Note that Interface types may not implement themselves or contain any cyclic references to each other.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] While types may share common fields in a GraphQL API, that may not always warrant the use of an Interface type to enforce that those fields remain consistently named.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Interface types are a powerful way to indicate shared behavior across the types that implement them.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] is a useful abstraction for humans and droids.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] GraphQL supports a second abstract type called a Union type.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Union types share similarities with Interface types, but they cannot define any shared fields among the constituent types.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Wherever we return a `SearchResult` type in our schema, we might get a `Human`, a `Droid`, or a `Starship`.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Note that members of a Union type need to be concrete Object types; you can’t define one using Interface types or other Union types as members.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] The `__typename` field is a special *meta-field* that automatically exists on every Object type and resolves to the name of that type, providing a way to differentiate between data types on the client.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Note that `name` is still specified on `Starship` because otherwise it wouldn’t show up in the results given that `Starship` is not a `Character`!
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Most of the examples we’ve covered on this page demonstrate how Object, Scalar, Enum, Interface, and Union types may be used as *output types* for the fields in a schema.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] But we have also seen that field arguments must specify their *input types*.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] So far, we’ve only talked about using scalar values (like Enums or String types) as an input type for a field argument.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] However, you can also pass complex objects as arguments using an Input Object type, which is the last kind of named types in GraphQL that we’ll explore.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] This is particularly valuable in the case of mutations, where you might want to pass in a whole object to be created.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] The fields on an Input Object type can refer to other Input Object types, but you can’t mix input and output types in your schema.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Input Object types also can’t have arguments on their fields.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In certain instances where field arguments are insufficient or certain common behaviors must be replicated in multiple locations, directives allow us to modify parts of a GraphQL schema or operation by using an `@` character followed by the directive’s name.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Directives may also be defined for use in GraphQL operations as *executable directives*.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Read more about executable directives on the Queries page.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] The GraphQL specification defines several built-in directives.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Note that, just like fields, directives can accept arguments and those arguments can have default values.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] The `@deprecated` directive has a nullable `reason` argument that accepts a `String` as an input type and falls back to `"No longer supported"`.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] And with directives, we must specify where they may be used, such as on a `FIELD_DEFINITION` or `ENUM_VALUE` for the `@deprecated` directive.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In addition to GraphQL’s built-in directives, you may define your own *custom directives*.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] As with custom Scalar types, it’s up to your chosen GraphQL implementation to determine how to handle custom directives during query execution.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] GraphQL allows you to add documentation to the types, fields, and arguments in a schema.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In fact, the GraphQL specification encourages you to do this in all cases unless the name of the type, field, or argument is self-descriptive.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Schema descriptions are defined using Markdown syntax and can be multiline or single line.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] In addition to making a GraphQL API schema more expressive, descriptions are helpful to client developers because they are available in introspection queries and visible in developer tools such as GraphiQL.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Occasionally, you may need to add comments in a schema that do not describe types, fields, or arguments, and are not meant to be seen by clients.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Now that you understand the key features of the type system, you’re ready to learn more about how to query data from a GraphQL API.
[src:graphql/learn-schema] Understand how to structure GraphQL queries to request exactly the data you need — including fields, variables and fragments.
